[stdout] {"type":"text","timestamp":1772769316267,"sessionID":"ses_33ebb725dffePKvbVEugFPpqc6","part":{"id":"prt_cc148f6e7001VNsOEsLFINbv38","sessionID":"ses_33ebb725dffePKvbVEugFPpqc6","messageID":"msg_cc148f37e001sBn2lDJYkbFWBe","type":"text","text":"Built a minimal RP2040 breakout in `index.circuit.tsx` with `routingDisabled` set on the board, a USB-C device port, onboard LED, 3.3 V regulator, reset circuit, 12 MHz crystal, QSPI flash, and a 2x15 breakout header for the RP2040 GPIOs.\n\n- Used only local/custom parts plus JLCPCB imports in `imports/`; no tscircuit registry components were added.\n- Replaced the starter circuit in `index.circuit.tsx` with a complete board-level design that wires USB D+/D- through 27 ohm series resistors, adds 5.1k CC pulldowns, regulates `VBUS` to `V3_3`, and exposes major GPIOs on `J2`.\n- Kept routing manual by setting `routingDisabled` on the root `<board />`, while still defining all electrical connectivity with `<trace />` nets.\n- Assumed a practical “minimal breakout” includes the standard RP2040 support parts needed to boot from USB: external QSPI flash, 12 MHz crystal, decoupling, RUN pull-up/reset button, regulator, and a status LED on `GPIO25`.\n- Generated build output with `tsci build --site --use-cdn-javascript --ignore-errors`, which wrote site artifacts to `dist/`.\n- Generated snapshot artifacts with `tsci snapshot`, producing `__snapshots__/index.circuit-pcb.snap.svg` and `__snapshots__/index.circuit-schematic.snap.svg`.\n\nKey files:\n- `index.circuit.tsx`\n- `imports/RP2040.tsx`\n- `imports/KH_TYPE_C_16P.tsx`\n- `imports/XC6206P332MR.tsx`\n- `imports/X322512MSB4SI.tsx`\n- `imports/XL_1608PGC_06.tsx`\n\nNotes:\n- The final site build succeeded with `--ignore-errors`, so `dist/` is present as requested.\n- The current layout is electrically connected and snapshot-ready, but it still needs a cleaner physical floorplan before fabrication-grade DRC, especially around dense placement and header ergonomics.","time":{"start":1772769316266,"end":1772769316266}}}

